nt of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Vaz","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Antonio, Manuel, Luis, Alfredo, Alvaro, Joaquin, Jorge, Mario, Victorio, Adriano, Aires, Amandio.  Portuguese Joao, Damiao, Afonso, Henrique, Joaquim, Ligia, Nelio, Paulo.","Portuguese: patronymic from   Vasco  . This surname is also found on the west coast of India, where it was taken by Portuguese colonists."],"variants":[{"name":"Vasco","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Fernando, Angel, Arnando, Arturo, Carlos, Dominga, Enrique, Jairo, Luis, Luz, Sergio.  Italian Carmine, Dante, Giro, Giuseppe, Michelangelo, Nunzi.","Spanish and Italian: ethnic name from <i>vasco</i> ‘Basque’, denoting someone from the Basque Country, or from a Spanish byname or Italian personal name of the same derivation. The inhabitants of this region, which extends between southern France and northern Spain, are first recorded in Latin sources as the <i>Vascones</i>, a word of unexplained etymology. See also   Gascoigne  . The Basques’ own name for themselves is <i>Euskaldun</i>. Compare   Basco  .","Spanish and Portuguese: old personal name corresponding to   Velasco  ."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]},{"name":"IV.","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Vivian   and   Vivien ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Walter IV. von Vaz was born in 1222 as the son of Walter III. VON VAZ and Adelheid VON RAPPERSWILL. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Adelheid von Montfort. He died after 1246, in Schleid, Saxe-Weimar-Eisenach, Germany."},"et":{"1222–Aft 1246":"1222–pärast 1246","1222–1246":"1222–1246","1203–Female":"1203–Surnud","1238–1343":"1238–1343","1240–1285":"1240–1285","–1254":"–1254","–Female":"Surnud","Aft 1246":"pärast 1246","1238":"1238","1203":"1203","1246":"1246","1222":"1222","um 1240":"umbes 1240","1343":"1343","1254":"1254","1285":"1285","1240":"1240","ABT 1238":"umbes 1238","Schweiz":"Schleid, Großherz